gomodel:SYNGO_3840  a     owl:Ontology ;
        rdfs:comment      "Rationale: Fig.6: \"Neto2 Ser-409 phosphorylation inhibits synaptic targeting of GluK1 in CA1 pyramidal neurons\"\n- \"As previously reported, we found a substantial increase in GluK1 synaptic responses in the presence of Neto2 WT (Fig. 6A). Co-expression of GluK1 with the phosphodeficient mutant Neto2 S409A also showed a similar increase in synaptic responses (Fig. 6B). By contrast, there was significantly less enhancement of synaptic currents when co-expressed with Neto2 S409D, the phosphomimetic mutant (Fig. 6, C and D). We have previously shown that Neto2 itself does not regulate AMPAR-mediated synaptic transmission (9). Taken together, these results show that when Neto2 is phosphorylated at Ser-409 the synaptic targeting of GluK1 is inhibited.\". Experimental description: - \"rat hippocampal slice cultures were biolistically transfected \"\n- Species of over-expressed Neto2 is not stated in the publication. The authors were contacted for additional information (dd 2/7/2018, rochek@ninds.nih.gov). Answer:\n\n\"Dear Pim van Nierop,\n\nHere is the species information for all the constructs used/ experiments conducted. Hope this is the information you are looking for. Please let me know if you have any other questions.\n\nFig. 1, 2 and 3\nGST-Neto1 (C-tail)- Mouse\nGST-Neto2 (C-tail)- Rat\n\nFig. 4A-4D\nOverexpression of Neto2 in heterologous cells- Rat\n\nFig. 4E\nDetection of endogenous phosphorylation from mouse brain- no overexpression\n\nFig. 5 and 6\nOverexpression of Neto2 and mutants- Rat\n\nBest,\nRicha Lomash.\"" ;
        lego:modelstate   "production" ;
        dc:contributor    "https://orcid.org/0000-0002-2514-0216" , "https://orcid.org/0000-0003-0593-3443" , "https://orcid.org/0000-0002-2286-1587" ;
        dc:date           "2018-07-03" ;
        dc:title          "SYNGO_BP_3840" ;
        pav:providedBy    "https://syngo.vu.nl" ;
